4.problem_text:
When the force on an object depends on the position of the object, we cannot find the work done by it on the object by simply multiplying the force by the displacement. The reason is that there is no one value for the force-it changes. So, we must find the work in tiny little displacements and then add up all the work results. We effectively say, "Yes, the force varies over any given tiny little displacement, but the variation is so small we can approximate the force as being constant during the displacement." Sure, it is not precise, but if we make the displacements infinitesimal, then our error becomes infinitesimal and the result becomes precise. But, to add an infinite number of work contributions by hand would take us forever, longer than a semester. So, we add them up via an integration, which allows us to do all this in minutes (much less than a semester).

Force $\vec{F}=\left(3 x^2 \mathrm{~N}\right) \hat{\mathrm{i}}+(4 \mathrm{~N}) \hat{\mathrm{j}}$, with $x$ in meters, acts on a particle, changing only the kinetic energy of the particle. How much work is done on the particle as it moves from coordinates $(2 \mathrm{~m}, 3 \mathrm{~m})$ to $(3 \mathrm{~m}, 0 \mathrm{~m})$ ?The unit of answer should be  J

0.problem_text:
When the force on an object depends on the position of the object, we cannot find the work done by it on the object by simply multiplying the force by the displacement. The reason is that there is no one value for the force-it changes. So, we must find the work in tiny little displacements and then add up all the work results. We effectively say, "Yes, the force varies over any given tiny little displacement, but the variation is so small we can approximate the force as being constant during the displacement." Sure, it is not precise, but if we make the displacements infinitesimal, then our error becomes infinitesimal and the result becomes precise. But, to add an infinite number of work contributions by hand would take us forever, longer than a semester. So, we add them up via an integration, which allows us to do all this in minutes (much less than a semester).

How much work is done on the particle as it moves from coordinates $(2 \mathrm{~m}, 3 \mathrm{~m})$ to $(3 \mathrm{~m}, 0 \mathrm{~m})$ ?The unit of answer should be  J

What pressure would $131.0 \mathrm{g}$ of xenon gas in a vessel of volume $1.0 \mathrm{dm}^3$ exert at $25^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ assume it behaved as a perfect gas? The unit of answer should be $\mathrm{atm}$. The answer is recorded as Answer[4]

A certain vibrating system satisfies the equation $u^{\prime \prime}+\gamma u^{\prime}+u=0$. Find the value of the damping coefficient $\gamma$ for which the quasi period of the damped motion is $UNK_3(a constant calculated by adding the sum of Answer[4] to the number (26.00). )$ \% greater than the period of the corresponding undamped motion. The unit of answer should be. The answer is recorded as Answer[3]

A vessel of volume $UNK_2(a constant calculated by adding the sum of Answer[3] to the number (20.91). ) \mathrm{dm}^3$ contains $2.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{H}_2$ and $1.0 \mathrm{~mol} \mathrm{~N}_2$ at $273.15 \mathrm{~K}$. Calculate their total pressure.The unit of answer should be $\mathrm{atm}$. The answer is recorded as Answer[2]

The dye dilution method is used to measure cardiac output with $UNK_1(a constant calculated by adding the sum of Answer[3] to the number (4.51). ) \mathrm{mg}$ of dye. The dye concentrations, in $\mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{L}$, are modeled by $c(t)=20 t e^{-0.6 t}, 0 \leqslant t \leqslant 10$, where $t$ is measured in seconds. Find the cardiac output.The unit of answer should be  $\mathrm{L}/\mathrm{min}$. The answer is recorded as Answer[1]

Calculate $\Delta G$ for the isothermal expansion of $UNK_0(a constant calculated by adding the sum of Answer[2, 4] to the number (-24.75). ) \mathrm{~mol}$ of an ideal gas at $325 \mathrm{~K}$ from an initial pressure of 12.0 bar to a final pressure of 2.5 bar. The unit of answer should be  $10^3 \mathrm{~J}$.. The answer is recorded as Answer[0]

Please use the answers to the above questions to perform the following calculations:
Please calculate the value of Answer[0]*Answer[1]*Answer[2]*Answer[3]*Answer[4]. Conclude the answer by stating 'The answer is therefore \boxed{[ANSWER]}.'
